1) Concepts of myth and mythology, sources for the study of mythology, main scholarly approaches in the field of mythology, important myth scholars;
2) Myths and other folklore genres that convey mythological notions, their peculiarities and division of labour (mythological knowledge reflected in songs, fairy tales, legends, customs and rituals);
3) Various aspects of mythological thought (cosmologies and eschatologies, creation myths of human beings and other species, mythical animals and humans, sky gods and chtonic deities, high and low mythology, sacred places and rituals);
4) Comparison of mythologies of different peoples (myths of Finno-Ugric peoples vs myths of Indo-European peoples);
5) Borders and applications of myths and mythologies (children mythology, pseudo mythology, national mythology, uses of mythology in media, art and literature).Objectives/eesmärkid:  To give basic knowledge about mythology as an academic field of study, incl. central concepts, sources and scholarly approaches. To introduce most important theories of myth, folklore genres that convey mythological knowledge, and diversity of mythical concepts among different peoples around the world.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After this course a student
1) can orientate oneself in basic concepts, most widespread scholarly approaches and soucres in the study of mythology;
2) has basic knowledge about most important theories of myth, about their applications in various disciplines as well as about the most significant scholars of mythology;
3) is able to recognise mythological motifs in different folklore genres and locate mythological notions of Estonian folk tradition in the wider international context;
4) has some knowledge about the myths of different peoples all over the world.
